# reel2md

`reel2md` is a local-first CLI that turns a reel or short-form video URL into a timestamped Markdown file for later use with AI tools.

## What it does

1. Resolve the URL with `yt-dlp` metadata.
2. Build a stable output path like `instagram_ABC123.md`.
3. Download the reel locally.
4. Extract scene-change frames with `ffmpeg`.
5. Run OCR on frames with `tesseract`.
6. Ask a local Ollama vision model to describe each frame.
7. Transcribe speech with Whisper.
8. Merge everything into one Markdown file.

## Prerequisites

Install these system tools and make sure they are on your `PATH`:

- `ffmpeg`
- `tesseract`
- `ollama`

You also need an Ollama vision model available locally. Example:

```powershell
ollama pull llava
```

For Instagram and other sites that require a logged-in browser session, use the cookies option:

```powershell
reel2md "https://www.instagram.com/reel/..." --cookies-from-browser chrome
```

## Install

From this folder:

```powershell
pip install -e .
```

## Usage

Run the dependency checker:

```powershell
reel2md doctor
```

Convert a reel:

```powershell
reel2md "https://www.instagram.com/reel/..." --cookies-from-browser chrome
```

Useful options:

```text
--output-dir PATH         Directory for final markdown files
--vision-model NAME       Ollama vision model to use
--whisper-model NAME      Whisper model size, e.g. base or small
--scene-threshold FLOAT   FFmpeg scene threshold, default 0.35
--skip-ocr                Disable OCR
--skip-vision             Disable Ollama vision descriptions
--skip-transcription      Disable Whisper transcription
--keep-temp               Keep intermediate files
--force                   Reprocess even if the markdown file exists
```

## Output shape

Each run writes one `.md` file with YAML frontmatter and timestamped steps:

```md
---
source: https://www.instagram.com/reel/...
platform: instagram
video_id: Cx123Abc
title: Example Reel
duration_seconds: 42
processed_at: 2026-05-26T23:00:00+05:30
---

# Example Reel

## Steps

**[00:00-00:05]**
- Spoken: First connect VCC to 3.3 volts.
- Visual: Close-up of an ESP32 dev board wired to a sensor module.
- On-screen text: GPIO 34 | VCC | GND
```

## Notes

- The CLI keeps the output focused on extracted evidence. It does not invent a bill of materials or summary with a second model pass.
- If you want an Obsidian or RAG layer later, that can sit on top of this output without changing the ingestion pipeline.

